	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=61489><span id=Scholar>Kamlatir, Eater of Souls</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>66 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.10]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I'm glad you appreciated my post Mokerr =)<br><br>Dumpin all of your points in sta and str is a good move, it will help you alot as you level up. My experience from playing a human sk is that the only thing I would want to change is my hp's and therefore my stamina. Also, sta is a hard stat to raise and still maintain your ac unlike str. You have a troll sk too and that will also help out. Hp seems to be dependant on your race, your sta and your class. As you level you get an increase in your hp based on these three factors. It's probably something along the lines of getting bonus hp per sta point because you're a troll and then a little something because you're an sk instead of a ranger =)<br><br>As to your question, in the post 50 game you will sometimes be passed over for a warrior, that's just the way it is but it's most often because you are lower level than the warrior. It also depends on race of course, I'd rather have an ogre sk as main then a de warrior. However, levels are most important. If I was a cleric and had a group in Seb looking for a tank I'd go with the 57 sk over the 52 warrior any day of the week, even though the warrior might have a little more hp's. Reason for this is that you receive a level penalty of a kind when you fight red cons. Fighting a red you'll get hit more often and for the maximum damage alot more times then someone higher then you and therefore lose more hp. <br><br>Once I got into a group that had a level 51 cleric as a healer. The enchanter was about my level and the rest somewhere in between. The cleric kept saying we needed a tank and I thought she simply hadn't realized that I had joined the group. Unfortunatly, she had, she just didn't know better. Buffed by a shaman and a cleric I have about 3900 hp's and 1200 ac ( and in no way do I have any kind of &quot;uber&quot; gear, I have Thurgadin quest armor or equivalent in most slots and some better items ), more then enough to tank most camps in Seb. Since I'm level 58 I also have a defensive of 250 or so and I can basically fight a slowed mob in Seb without losing a single hp. Some people are however not aware of the basic game mechanics that govern this game, or are too stupid to see them. The chanter in this group gave me a tell saying that she had just mistimed a complete heal and gotten the ogre warrior previously in group killed. He then left, and that was why they needed a new tank. The following day I zone into Seb, ooc that I'm looking for a group. Within five seconds I get a tell from the same cleric asking me to join her group. I politely declined, for obvious reasons (I don't want to die due to her incompetence). I've heard many say that they actually prefer a shadowknight as a tank in some zones (including Seb) due to the fact that we can taunt so well that casters don't have to worry about getting summoned or being hit on. The warrior main tank concept mostly applies to very high level encounters such as Ixiblat Fer (part of cleric epic), Overking in Chardok, Lhranc (final mob in sk epic) etc. I've personally gone down in Chardok with a single group and fought my way to the Prince, a level 61 mob. We of course preceeded to kill the Prince, with me as a tank. Even though I know many will disagree I say that sometimes sk's are even better tanks then warriors. Just take summoning mobs. A warrior tanks it and then needs a complete heal, cleric gets summoned. An sk does the same and due to the spells the clerics can ch as much as they want and still not get summoned. However, this is all of course dependandt on the player behind the character. Bad players exist in plenty on all servers, wether they be warrior, sk, ranger or cleric and I've met level 60 players from the suposedly better guilds on my server that I wouldn't give 2 cents for in a tight spot. They can usually manage a basic exp group but if the going gets tough they fold. Part of playing EQ in my experience is keeping a mental list of which players to group with and which to avoid, it all gets so much easier then.<br><br>Anyway, I digress (was that cleric that got me started again hehe), as a troll sk with alot of points in sta you'll be able to tank pretty much everything but the most high level encounters and I almost never get passed up for a warrior and if you ever do, see level 51 cleric part above, the group passing probably just doesn't know better. Also, you make a name for yourself post 50, a name that will follow you around for the rest of your EQ life. If you have a good reputation you'll get into groups just based on that. Just remember that everything is a group effort and to pick the right players for your group, else no class or level in the world helps <br><br>Kamlatir<br>58 shadowknight<br>Far Seekers, The Rathe<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Feb 16 12:55:22 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br></td></td></tr>
